"Raihani N., Aitken D.","Uncertainty, rationality and cooperation in the context of climate change",2011,"Climatic Change","108","1",,"47","55",,,10.1007/s10584-010-0014-4,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80052267478&partnerID=40&md5=7431f9e223b8a62e7f5f179ca4d45ba5","Institute of Zoology, Zoological Society of London, London NW1 4RY, United Kingdom; Environmental Change Institute, University of Oxford, Oxford OX1 3QY, United Kingdom","Raihani, N., Institute of Zoology, Zoological Society of London, London NW1 4RY, United Kingdom; Aitken, D., Environmental Change Institute, University of Oxford, Oxford OX1 3QY, United Kingdom","Climate change represents the largest social dilemma humans have ever faced, where individual actors maximise their personal gain by emitting greenhouse gases into the atmosphere even though this is detrimental to the collective global good. Cooperation on a global scale is urgently required if we are to overcome this problem. However, this is difficult to achieve because cooperators pay the cost of reducing emissions while any benefits are shared between cooperators and free-riders alike. In a risk-free, rational world cooperative behaviour can be promoted through mechanisms that increase the benefit of cooperating relative to free-riding, such as rewards or sanctions. In reality, however, outcomes are seldom certain and humans rarely behave rationally when confronted with risky prospects. Here, we argue that effective policies to mitigate global climate change should incorporate mechanisms to foster cooperation, but also account for both uncertainty and irrational responses that may inhibit collective action. © 2011 Springer Science+Business Media B.V.",,"Collective action; Free-riders; Free-riding; Global climate changes; Global scale; Social dilemmas; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Behavioral research; climate change; collective action; cooperative behavior; emission control; environmental economics; environmental planning; environmental policy; global perspective; greenhouse gas; optimization; risk assessment; uncertainty analysis",,,,,,"Adger, N., Aggarwal, P., Agrawala, S., Alcamo, J., Alliali, A., Anisimov, O., Arnell, N., Yohe, G., (2007) Climate Change 2007: Impacts, Adaptation and Vulnerability, Summary For Policymakers, , IPCC Secretariat, c/o WMO, 7bis, Avenue de la Paix, C. P. No 2300, 1211 Geneva 2, Switzerland; Barclay, P., Altruism as a courtship display: some effects of third-party generosity on audience perceptions (2010) Brit J Psych, 101, pp. 123-135; Barclay, P., Willer, R., Partner choice creates competitive altruism in humans (2007) Proc R Soc B, 274, pp. 749-753; Barrett, S., (2002) Towards a Better Climate Treaty, , (AEI-Brookings Joint Center for Regulatory Studies); Barrett, S., McIlveen, R., (2009) Negotiating the Next Climate Change Treaty, , London: Pol Exch; Barrett, S., Stavins, R., Increasing participation and compliance in international climate change agreements (2003) Int Environ Agreements: Politics Law Econ, 3, pp. 349-376; Bazerman, M., Carroll, J.S., Negotiator cognition (1987) Research in Organisational Behavior, Vol 9, pp. 247-288. , B. Staw and L. L. Cummings (Eds.), Greenwich: JAI Press; Boyd, R., Gintis, H., Bowles, S., Richerson, P.J., The evolution of altruistic punishment (2003) Proc Natl Acad Sci USA, 100, pp. 3531-3535; Boyd, R., Gintis, H., Bowles, S., Coordinated punishment of defectors sustains cooperation and can proliferate when rare (2010) Science, 328, pp. 617-620; Buchan, N.R., Grimalda, G., Wilson, R., Brewer, M., Fatas, E., Foddy, M., Globalization and human cooperation (2008) Proc Natl Acad Sci USA, 106, pp. 4138-4142; Cinyabugama, M., Page, T., Putterman, L., Cooperation under the threat of expulsion in a public goods experiment (2005) J Public Econ, 89, pp. 1421-1435; Dreber, A., Nowak, M.A., Gambling for global goods (2008) Proc Natl Acad Sci USA, 105, pp. 2261-2262; Edwards, A., Elwyn, G., Covey, J., Matthews, E., Pill, R., Presenting risk information-a review of the effects of ""framing"" and other manipulations on patient outcomes (2001) J Health Comm, 6, pp. 61-82; Fehr, E., Fischbacher, U., The nature of human altruism (2003) Nature, 425, pp. 785-791; Fehr, E., Gächter, S., Altruistic punishment in humans (2002) Nature, 415, pp. 137-140; Finus, M., The enforcement mechanisms of the Kyoto protocol: flawed of promising concepts (2008) Lett Spat Resour Sci, 1, pp. 13-25; Fischbacher, U., Gächter, S., Fehr, E., Are people conditionally cooperative? Evidence from a public goods experiment (2001) Econ Lett, 71, pp. 397-404; Frederick, S., Loewenstein, G., O'Donoghue, T., Time discounting and time preference: a critical review (2002) J Econ Lit, 40, pp. 351-401; Gagnier, D., Climategate: Bad science, red herring or political and media football? (2010) Policy Options, pp. 74-78; Human impact on climate change: The anatomy of a silent crisis (2009) Geneva, Global Humanitarian Forum 116, , Global Humanitarian Forum; Goldstein, N.J., Cialdini, R.B., Griskevicius, V., A room with a viewpoint: using social norms to motivate environmental conservation in hotels (2008) J Consum Res, 35, pp. 472-482; Griskevicius, V., Cialdini, R.B., Goldstein, N.J., Social norms: an underestimated and underemployed lever for managing climate change (2008) Int J Sust Comm, 3, pp. 5-13; Griskevicius, V., Tybur, J.M., van den Bergh, B., Going green to be seen: status, reputation, and conspicuous conservation (2010) J Pers Soc Psych, 98, pp. 392-404; Hamilton, W.D., The genetical evolution of social behaviour (1964) J Theor Biol, 7, pp. 1-16; Hardin, G., The tragedy of the commons (1968) Science, 162, pp. 1243-1248; Heffernan, O., Constructive communication (2010) Nature Rep Clim Change, 4, p. 1; Helm, D., (2008) Credible Energy Policy, , London: Pol Exch; Henrich, N., Henrich, J., Cooperation through reciprocity and reputation (2007) Why Humans Cooperate, pp. 109-132. , UK: Oxford University Press; Henry, L.A